The Natural Hazards Engineering Research Infrastructure (NHERI) is supported by the National Science Foundation (NSF) as a distributed, multi-user national facility that provides the natural hazards research community with access to research infrastructure that includes earthquake, wave and wind engineering experimental facilities, cyberinfrastructure, computational modeling and simulation tools, and research data, as well as education and community outreach activities. The 12-fan Wall of Wind (WOW) at Florida International University (FIU) is one of the shared-use national Experimental Facilities (EFs) for NSF’s NHERI program that provides access and expertise to users across the nation to conduct ground-breaking research with its state-of-the-art wind engineering experimental resources. The WOW is a large open jet facility with pioneering capabilities to simulate wind effects on the built environment. The WOW testing facility provides distinct advantages over conventional smaller lower speed wind tunnels, including:

High-speed holistic full-scale testing in simulated hurricane wind speeds up to and including ~160 mph (Category 5 on Saffir-Simpson scale) with various exposures and turbulence parameters;
System-level destructive tests to study progressive damage and failure modes of systems, sub-assemblies, components, and connections to improve their designs and performance; 
Wind-driven rain simulations to study water intrusion through building envelopes; 
Testing under extreme wind and rain environments to develop innovative mitigation devices to attenuate wind damage and rain infiltration, and to validate efficacy and system-level integrity; 
Aerodynamic/aeroelastic testing of large models in ABL flows at high Reynolds numbers (Re) to minimize scaling errors, allow higher sensor resolution, and better simulate finer architectural details. 


Thus, the EF offers unique experimental and infrastructure resources to provide full- and large-scale testing capabilities for wind engineering research that do not exist elsewhere in the U.S. at comparable scale.

Wind hazards have caused significant impacts to humans and infrastructure in the U.S. The scientific vision of the NHERI WOW EF is to enable frontier research and education to impart resiliency and sustainability to new and existing building and cladding systems, and to lifeline infrastructure, thus preventing wind hazards from becoming community disasters. Holistic testing of large models and integrated component assemblies is helping NSF-supported external users gain new knowledge on wind and rain damage, cascading failures, and structural/functional fragilities, both with and without retrofitting strategies. The EF is helping to research and develop novel sustainable building and adaptive fa&ccedil;ade concepts. The EF is also allowing, for the first time, large-scale testing of power and traffic infrastructure to understand and reduce vulnerabilities. The new Partial Turbulence Simulation (PTS) approach allows testing of large-scale models to estimate peak wind loads on structures incorporating the effect of both the high and low frequency turbulence. This is creating new fundamental knowledge on bluff-body aerodynamics in high Reynolds number (Re) flows. Although developed in the WOW EF, the PTS approach can be used in conventional wind tunnels to better predict full-scale wind loads.

The EF’s Science Plan is disseminated to the natural hazards research community, and research findings are used to improve standards and practices and strengthen resiliency. The updated ASCE/SEI Standard on Wind Tunnel Testing for Buildings and Other Structures (ASCE/SEI:49-21) and the ASCE/SEI Minimum Design Loads and Associated Criteria for Buildings and Other Structures (ASCE/SEI:7-22) have important contributions from WOW EF research, including the PTS method, wind effects on pavers, and wind loads on canopies and elevated houses.

The WOW has been successfully implementing effective educational tools and methods since its inception. The EF team conducts User Workshops and hosts external students for the NHERI Research Experiences for Undergraduates (REU) program. The current NHERI period marked the successful Research Experience for Teachers (RET) program at the WOW. These K-12 teachers worked with students and EF team to acquire new knowledge to be translated into new educational materials in their classrooms. In coordination with the EF team, the teachers also organized summer workshops for other local teachers. Middle and high school educators participated in this Wind Engineering for Science Teachers (WEST) professional development workshops.

The United States has learned very hard lessons in the last decade about its human, economic, and infrastructure vulnerabilities to wind hazard events. The outcomes covering the entire life of the award pertain to the frontier research and education facilitated by the NHERI WOW EF to advance knowledge and foster transformative mitigation measures, to reduce loss of life, damage, and economic loss. The goal is to improve design practices for structural and building envelope systems and lifeline infrastructures to create more wind-resilient and sustainable communities. The WOW promoted student and teacher learning as part of the larger national effort to foster a diverse and globally competitive STEM workforce. More broadly, the WOW continues to serve the national interest by promoting the progress of wind engineering science and technology; generating innovations that can lead to more resilient comminutes; and supporting research needed to prevent wind hazards from becoming societal disasters.

